<text>Controling multiple models with a single controller

&lt; Previous | Index | Next &gt;

In the previous section, you have learned how to use a controller to control a model. If you have multiple models on the same page, you may want to have a single controller that can interact with more than one model. For example, you may want to have buttons that can start, stop and reset two models at the same time upon being clicked (so that the user can compare the simulations):

  
   
[These are two embedded simulators.]

To set up the above example, you have to insert a set of Activity Buttons (select &quot;Insert&gt;Activity Controller&gt;Activity Button&quot;), choose the &quot;Script&quot; item from the &quot;Action&quot; drop-down list, and then type in the scripts needed to control the models, as is illustrated in the image below:

  
[This is a screenshot.]

Another example is that you may want to set the properties of the models with single controllers:

   
[These are two embedded Jmol viewers.]

Note that in order to use this functionality, you need to know how to use the MW/  Jmol scripts.

 
Tip: If scripts are long and you will need to write them in a more comfortable way, use your favorite  text editor to write scripts and copy back to the text area. If there exist scripts already, copy them to your editor first before editing them.
 

